Osteoporosis represents the most common bone disease worldwide and results in a 
significantly increased fracture risk. Extrinsic and intrinsic factors 
implicated in the development of osteoporosis are also associated with delayed 
fracture healing and impaired bone regeneration. Based on a steadily increasing 
life expectancy in modern societies, the global implications of osteoporosis and 
impaired bone healing are substantial. Research in the last decades has revealed 
several molecular pathways that stimulate bone formation and could be targeted 
to treat both osteoporosis and impaired fracture healing. The identification and 
development of therapeutic approaches modulating bone formation, rather than 
bone resorption, fulfils an essential clinical need, as treatment options for 
reversing bone loss and promoting bone regeneration are limited. This review 
focuses on currently available and future approaches that may have the potential 
to achieve these aims.

